data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both work exactly like any other unmanaged type with `stackalloc`:

```csharp
Span<nint>  signed   = stackalloc nint[4];
Span<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system each element is 8 bytes. On a 32-bit runtime they'd be 4 bytes. The only caveat encountered was that `sizeof(nint)` requires an `unsafe` context (use `IntPtr.Size` instead).
